Fix server lockup on 'status' when a client name exceeds 16 chars.

SV_Status_f declared the padding width 'l' as size_t. When a connected
player's name is longer than 16 chars (or the address string longer than
22), '16 - strlen(...)' underflows to a huge unsigned value, and the
padding loop 'for (j = 0; j < l; j++)' (j promoted to size_t) runs ~2^64
times -> the server main thread hangs, locking up the whole server. This
is reachable via console or rcon 'status' and is a regression from vanilla
Quake II, where 'l' was int (negative -> loop skipped).

Make 'l' int again and cast strlen so the subtraction is signed.

diff --git a/src/server/sv_cmd.c b/src/server/sv_cmd.c
index 893ee10..ca41f40 100644
--- a/src/server/sv_cmd.c
+++ b/src/server/sv_cmd.c
@@ -394,7 +394,7 @@ static void
 SV_Status_f(void)
 {
 	int i, j;
-	size_t l;
+	int l;
 	client_t *cl;
 	char *s;
 	int ping;
@@ -435,7 +435,7 @@ SV_Status_f(void)
 		}
 
 		Com_Printf("%s", cl->name);
-		l = 16 - strlen(cl->name);
+		l = 16 - (int)strlen(cl->name);
 
 		for (j = 0; j < l; j++)
 		{
@@ -446,7 +446,7 @@ SV_Status_f(void)
 
 		s = NET_AdrToString(cl->netchan.remote_address);
 		Com_Printf("%s", s);
-		l = 22 - strlen(s);
+		l = 22 - (int)strlen(s);
 
 		for (j = 0; j < l; j++)
 		{
